{
  "text": "Alterations in expression of components of the PI3K/Akt/mTOR occur in 42% of primary prostate tumors and 100% of metastatic tumors [CITATION_1] . Thus, targeting the PI3K/Akt/mTOR pathway is considered a promising approach for the treatment of CRPC [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . To determine a possible role of this pathway, western blot analysis was performed to assess the status of this pathway in LNCaP95-DR cells. We found no significant change in the expression levels of proteins related to the PI3K/Akt/mTOR pathway, with the exception of pS6 ( Figures 3B and A1C) . However, the mTOR inhibitor, everolimus, did not mediate differential effects in the different cell lines (Figure A1D ), which could suggest that an increased pS6 expression was not important for the acquired resistance to docetaxel.",
